<paragraph blockId="4.[128,654,1544,1753]" lastBlockId="4.[701,1228,1550,1752]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
The following combination of features distinguishes 
<taxonomicName authorityName="STIASSNY &amp; SCHLIEWEN" authorityYear="2007" box="[293,452,1640,1664]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Congochromis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[293,452,1640,1664]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Congochromis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pellegrin" authorityYear="1904" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Nanochromis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Nanochromis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: only the last three to five pored scales of the upper lateral line are contiguous with the dorsal-fin base (vs. at least the posterior half of the upper lateral line contiguous); fully scaled nape, and partially scaled chest and cheek (vs. an asquamate nape, chest, and cheek); jaw teeth relatively robust unicuspids, not closely spaced (vs. extremely fine, closely spaced unicuspids); and the presence of a small, supraneural bone (vs. absence).
</paragraph>
